<div class="post-3561 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-counterculture-history tag-40th-anniversary-of-hip-hop tag-afrika-bambaataa tag-birth-of-hip-hop tag-kool-herc tag-universal-zulu-nation">
	<h2 id="post-3561"><a href="http://stevenhager420.wordpress.com/2013/08/19/when-did-hip-hop-begin/" rel="bookmark">When did hip hop&nbsp;begin?</a></h2>
			<p class="comments"><a href="http://stevenhager420.wordpress.com/2013/08/19/when-did-hip-hop-begin/#comments">with 3 comments</a></p>
	
	<div class="main">
		<p><a href="http://stevenhager420.files.wordpress.com/2013/08/kool_herc_1.jpg"><img class="alignleft size-medium wp-image-3563" alt="kool_herc_1" src="http://stevenhager420.files.wordpress.com/2013/08/kool_herc_1.jpg?w=300&#038;h=199" width="300" height="199" /></a>Sorry to say I was out of town and missed last week&#8217;s 40th Anniversary of Hip Hop celebration in Central Park, but I was super happy to hear Kool Herc, Coke La Rock and Soul Sonic Force were part of the ceremony. Hopefully, the media will start giving more attention to the First Generation soon, the people who actually invented hip hop and many of whom remain impoverished and greatly under-appreciated.</p>
<p>By the way, most historians place the birth of hip hop as Kool Herc&#8217;s sister&#8217;s (Cindy)  birthday party, August 13, 1973.</p>
<p>Herc gave a powerful speech at the event: &#8220;Instead of making it rain in the strip club, make it drizzle in the daycare center&#8230; It&#8217;s about people respecting people, that&#8217;s what hip hop&#8217;s supposed to be&#8230; How many Trayvons got shot in Harlem last week, how many Trayvons got shot in Brooklyn last week?&#8221;</p>
<p>Recently, I learned Afrika Bambaataa, founder of the Universal Zulu Nation, has a different chronology and places the actual birth of hip hop in 1974, which makes next year the actual 40th Anniversary, not this year.</p>
<div id="attachment_739" style="width: 310px" class="wp-caption alignleft"><a href="http://stevenhager420.files.wordpress.com/2012/02/bambaataa121.jpg"><img class="size-medium wp-image-739" alt="Afrika Bambaataa at Bronx River Projects, photo by Sylvia Plachy" src="http://stevenhager420.files.wordpress.com/2012/02/bambaataa121.jpg?w=300&#038;h=202" width="300" height="202" /></a><p class="wp-caption-text">Afrika Bambaataa at Bronx River Projects, photo by Sylvia Plachy</p></div>
<p>Bam grew up in the Black Spades and became an important facilitator and communications expert in that society, the largest gang in NYC history.</p>
<p>But in the early 1970s, Bam sensed the tribal identity created by the Spades needed to evolve more into a culture based on the South Bronx arts of graffiti and breaking, instead of fighting. So instead of recruiting soldiers for street war, Bam began recruiting the most talented and creative teens to join the Universal Zulu Nation, the first hip hop society. This vision had been partially inspired by a recent trip to Africa.</p>
<p>So where do you place the birth of hip hop? With Herc&#8217;s break beat birthday party or with the tribal chief who first put djing, rapping, breaking and writing together and called that hybrid &#8220;Hip Hop?&#8221;</p>
<p>In fact, the movement of hip hop into the mainstream was begun by Bambaataa, who made the first uptown-downtown connections. Any interviews that talked about &#8220;hip hop&#8221; in the first few years of media coverage, were interviews with Bam because he was the only person pushing that tag on the culture.</p>
<p>If you have any interest in this world, I have several ebooks on the subject on my smashwords site, as well as the script for a film I wrote about the First Generation.</p>
